    Tutorial: Adding a Neighborhood Road Tile with a Hex Editor

    This process is actually a whole lot easier than deleting road tiles, but I figured the previous post was long enough already.

    As with the previous post, find the total number of road tiles, convert and reverse it in SimPE’s converter, then extract your neighborhood terrain.

    Open up the terrain in HxD, then search for the backwards hexadecimal number of road tiles and 00 00 02.

    Select the 02 at the end of what it found, then use shift+right arrow to keep selecting blocks of two until the hexadecimal length at the bottom says 7C.  The next non-highlighted number should be another 02.  Copy what you’ve got highlighted using Ctrl+C.

    Go back before that first 02 and paste using Ctrl+V.  (There are two different paste options on the right-click menu, and if you choose the wrong one, this won’t work.  Use Ctrl+V to be sure.)

    Go back up to the total number of road tiles and add one to it (feel free to use SimPE’s converter).  Save, exit, and go back to SimPE.  Make sure you hit “yes” when it asks you to reload – as before, it’ll help you catch errors, but we also need to edit the new road tile.  (Right now it’s sitting in the same place as the one we copied, so we won’t be able to see it if we load the game.)

    The new road tile will be the first one on the list.  Using @criquette-was-here‘s method, move the new road tile to the position you want it in.  Commit, save and load up the game.

    The new tile should be visible.  If there’s no tile where it ought to be, but the neighborhood terrain resource shows the correct number of road tiles and loads without an error, then you’ve probably made a mistake while moving it.  (I say so having done that while writing up the tutorial.)  You may have to flatten the terrain for it to be fully visible, or else give it uneven Z-values by using trees to find the heights at the corners – and don’t forget that you’ll have to figure out the correct orientation and texture to use for both it and its neighbors.  But you should have an extra road tile to work with now!
